segments.text: Full-time center managers.
And they had their respective areas that they were out constantly seeing what we could do.
Need study.
Learn need study.
And then the divisions, so we wouldn't have any conflict with the divisions, they signed their staff to that center.
And those staff that reported to their head of the division didn't report to the city manager.
The center manager had no administrative control over any of the people.
All his was from facilities, providing need studies, making sure the door was open when they spoke to me and so forth and so on.
And that was probably the greatest thing we did during my tenure.
We created those centers.
We were much more cost-effective in delivering our services.
We had availability of lots of good professional help.
You know, you might just need a lawyer for a two-hour presentation to take to an accident investigation or whatever.
And we had those available, of course, in these centers because it's all located in major areas.
And that was probably one of the
the best decisions that I made there at that time.
Not only for the engineering convention center, but for the entire university system.
Because we give them another organization represented in this grand system.
And they were always first class operations.
There was no piggyback.
They were always first class.
When we started to offer the
rig training, all-field rig training, and see the independent drillers come to me and say, look, we've got, this is about 12, 15 years ago, back in the early 80s, we need some trained rig workers.
So I said, well, here's what we're going to take.
And I said, we have to have a rig.
We have to have this.
And the independent drillers said they can give us the rig to train on.
They give us the, they underwrote the program,
which was rather expensive.
Billy Mac's kid went through it, his son went through it, and said it's the greatest train he ever had in his life.
But we believed no hands on the train.
We believed in theory, but we believed no hands on the train.
And so that was a great success.
It got us a lot of publicity with the legislature.
Bill Clements came out.
He was governor.
Looking back on those 19 years,
Is there any area of service, and I don't mean geographic area, but any topic that you wish you all could have done more?
Were you frustrated that you couldn't have served this or this or this industry?
We couldn't serve them.
We had no boundaries.
See, the Engineering Extension Service is the only agency in the state of Texas that has a statewide mandate to provide probation and technical training on an extension basis.
We had no condominium.
We saw something like you mentioned.
Yeah, we saw it, but we got on it.
We jumped on it right away.
And normally, in all those cases, there's some agency, some trade association, some technically role in it as far as the money raising is concerned.
What were your favorite groups to work with?
There must have been some that were more pleasant than others though.
Who were the key state officials that you worked with?
Don't you name your favorites.
The ones that you

would say thank you to I guess the one that probably was my favorite and I don't know why I say I don't know but anyway I like Mark White Mark White and I and Joe Reynolds see Joe Reynolds Reynolds and White was in the law practice together and White was his junior member and then when he made Secretary of State because I knew White when he was on the with the
as in his law firm.
And Mark White, the Secretary of State, come on up and run for governor.
I felt that he was the only governor I really, really knew.
You know, for any, I mean, I've known all the governors, but I mean, to really know them, so I guess that's one reason I felt it was close to him.
Of course, Bill Preston helped me out an awful lot.
Any time I wanted an appointment with any senator or representative, I could call Bill.
He'd hand me an appointment.
This was while he was?
State chairman.
Well, while he was a representative, and as he served, you know, he served as chairman of the House Appropriation Committee for about 10 or 12 years.
Whenever I wanted an appointment with any senator or house representative, I'd call Bill.
He'd hand me an appointment.
Of course, Bill Moore.
when he was in the Senate.
I had done a lot of other work for Bill Moore.
And on his outside, we had that back of A&M.
I wrote the chart for that back of A&M with Bill and .
Can you give me an example of lobbying at work, where you called somebody and they made the wheels turn?
Describe.
for a specific project?
If there was one, you can think of?
Yeah.
I can think of one for fire.
There was a big push to create two or three more fire fields in the state of Texas.
And they didn't want to be a part of A&M.
They wanted to create their own, take a bunch of volunteer fire departments.
They thought they should have their own fire field.
There was no way in the world it could ever support the town.
But still, the volunteer fire departments carry a lot of rank in rural areas with their elected representatives.
And so they put on a push to create a fire field somewhere out in Woodlands area.
This was long before the Woodlands was built.
And they bypassed us completely.
And I got a call one day from a member of the representative's name down in that area.
He said, what did I think about you?
It was Brazoria County that was pushing it so hard.
I think it was Brazoria County that was pushing it so hard that it was going to tie in with Harris County.
I said, well, it's a very expensive train program.
I said, it's not cheap.
I said, you've got to have good training.
You've got to be damn careful.
And I said, fuel's expensive, and you've got to burn.
You can't just light a match and say, here, now we're going to go put it out.
I said, if you're going to have any fire training or those types of training, you've got to have hands-on training.
They got to smell the heat and feel the heat.
But anyway, so he said, well, they're putting this consortium together now.
I know that they're going to be coming to this for appropriation.
So we got that started.
Now, the way I stopped it, I went down to the organizer.
I said, tell me, what do you guys want?
What do you want?
Tell me what you want.
Give me an opportunity to say no.
So finally, what their big gripe was, is volunteer fire department, they didn't have anybody to place the train on Saturday.
They opened the damn parking on Saturday morning.
And that was their big gripe.
You know, they worked five days a week, and they didn't have anybody to place the...
I don't know, it was too expensive to spend the night and so forth.
So I said, yeah, that's a problem.
What time do you want it?
You want it to open at 10 on Saturday?
Burn it till 6.
But we killed that one.
But another, at the same time, they were trying to get one out in West Texas.
And the word got to them then what we did.
But then they used the excuse that we live too far away.
We can't come that distance.
All right, can you give an example of where you needed some help in the legislature?
You needed to get a bill passed or some funding and give an example of where some people stepped up and helped the extension service.
No, I'll request one.
The only state appropriated money, the only state appropriated money, the way I used my state appropriated money was from the volunteer fire departments in the rural water district.
See, the rest of this is $3 million.
They didn't support our programs like PILAR and the great television.
No, we never, I don't ever, I didn't, I presented my, I worked with LBP.
I had the LVB over two months before anybody else did, and I was taking them through what my request was going to be.
But I had programs that the legislature couldn't fuss about.
Volunteer Fire Department, you know, rural water districts.
They couldn't fuss if there was a problem.
And it was, you know, even though we had a $39 million budget, it was only costing the state $3 million.
And we didn't even have any in-house fights with the board or other agencies.
In fact, I had
on numerous occasions challenged that detention service to get their money the way I got mine.
And John Dutch said one time that Bill Moore and I don't know, four or five others, along with at that time, I don't know who was the chancellor of the system, I guess he was about to answer that.
But anyway, he had them all.
And his main complaint was that he couldn't compete with us.
He had a different clientele.
All right, now you reported to Benson and Calhoun under Dr. Williams when you were first.
All right.
Dr. Williams has the heart attack, and then the system is recreated.
The chancellor of the system recreated in 76.
And Jarvis Miller becomes president.
Ludeke went in and served for Williams.
Right.
And tell them about working with General Ludeke.
No problem.
He and I, he was a general and I was a colonel, so I had to say yes, sir, and I knew it.
I didn't argue with him.
How long did it take him to make up his mind about something?
Well, when they told me I was going to move, that they were going to move the headquarters over to Henderson Hall,
And at that time Fred told me, now this is temporary.
And Dr. Wheaton told me this is temporary.
But they've all agreed with me that we had to get out of there.
It was that.
It was eyesore for the university.
And that's the approach I took.
It's not for me, it's, you know.
Now this is from that, down at the south.
We missed this all, yeah.
So Ludeke was in command when they were going to let the contract for Henderson Hall be fixed up.
When I went down there to see the plants, they had my reproduction shop up on the third floor.
And I always had my own reproduction facility.
You may say that's your home.
I admit it was probably your home.
But in industrial economics, I had my own reproduction facility.
So I could control the time.
I could move my projects around any way I wanted to.
So I had to deliver them.
But I had a reproduction shop from day one.
And a lot of people managed.
Now, this was for printing materials?
Yes.
All my artistic work.
Because all mine was sponsored research.
And, you know, when I brought down, and I had Exxon, I had contracts for Exxon for seven or eight straight years.
And you made it to their board.
Well, they expected a first class presentation.
They didn't want to see some carbon paper stuck out of it.
So I mean, I had, that was quality.
And that was built into the price to operate that thing.
That was built into the price.
But anyway, when I went down to see him, General Luther was in charge at that time.
I said, you know, we can't have that facility up on the third floor.
I said, well, I've only got one little bitty elevator.
And I said, there'll be stuff coming up and down.
And of course, I'd gone into really developing good lesson plans, good technical manuals.
And we had part of a reproduction shop still do that.
And they built that building out.
And by the way, we even paid for our building.
We built that $250,000 building out
We built the annex.
We built that $500,000.
Fred Benson put $500,000.
He put $500,000 out of the engine extension.
We built that bomb building.
We built that.
It has its materials.
I built that out of my feed.
I ask them whether it's right or wrong.
I operated the engine extension services.
I charged for everything.
There was no free things.
I mean, it was all built into the price.
And so we were able to do these kind of things.
But anyway, we got that to General Lukey's locale.
I said, well, let's put it down on the first floor so people can get in and get out.
And we moved that down.
Well, I called, who had that before?
Whoever had that chopper, he wanted to do it.
And General Lukey, out on the phone, said, right from his office.
Who was that guy that had that before?
I don't remember.
All right.
Then when General Ludeke steps aside, then Frank, let's see.
No, that's when Jarvis comes in.
Jarvis is president, and Dr. Williams is here for another couple of years.
How did your reporting process change then?
To whom did you report?
Well, they made Pinson vice president of engineering, so I still reported up to him for that.
Okay.
They didn't have, I guess I reported directly to Jarvis for continuing education, because I know I never did go up through Prescott.
Okay.
To my knowledge, I didn't.
But now you know I'd give them a continuing education after five years.
You know, I only took that job for five years.
So after five years, I'll
about continuing education.
And that fifth year came up just about the time Jarvis took over.
OK. All right.
So you then, by and large, reported to the system, not through the president's office.
Well, I can't say that, because I had to make my budget presentation one year to Jarvis.
OK. All right.
When he would have a staff meeting of his key people, did you meet with them?
All right.
No, the agency did.
All right, did Dr. Williams, did he, when he gathered the agencies, you met with them when he was chancellor?
Well, one or two meetings we had, yes.
All right.
All right, then when he left, Frank Hubert became the chancellor.
What, did the routine change at all?
It never changed.
Okay.
See, he was a Fred Benson man.
You knew that, Frank Hubert.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
The first thing he told me, the first thing he did when he became chancellor, was for his friend Vincent Sellard to attend Pat's office.
See, he liked Fred.
I mean, Fred and Dean.
I think they were family friends, too.
All right, then take me on up through the 80s.
Were there any changes in the routine with different presidents and different chancellors?
Well, of course, Richardson took over in 84.
All right, no matter.
Wait, we skipped the man from Purdue.
No, Hanson.
Hanson.
He was chancellor.
Well, it was about 84 when he did it.
Oh, and Richardson became dean of engineering.
Oh, I'm sorry.
Yeah, yeah.
He became dean of engineering.
All right.
And he was also vice chancellor.
Describe his management style.
Was it, it was less direct than Benson and Calhoun had been?
Herb never, the whole time that he was there, Herb never put a crossword.
Herb and I got along superbly.
I can't say enough good things about her, which is where I come from.
She never objected to a thing I wanted to do.
She proved everything I sent down to her.
I met with him once a month.
And it was no problem.
Where her problems was caused by his dad, Jack Flipsey, Kim, what was his name?
Kim Hall.
And we only had one conflict.
Now, you've got to realize I'm a very organized person.
I believe in an organizational chart.
I believe it, and I follow it.
But anyway, you want me to put this on tape?
Cut it off.
Let me just talk to you.
As you look back, you served 19 years.
under a number of different presidents and chancellors.
I'm not going to ask the negative, but in the positive, to which ones would you give the highest?
As many as you want to.
Which ones deserve the highest credit?
During that 19-year period?
Of course, I'd have to say Dr. Liggins in place number one.
Why?
But I just think he is more knowledgeable about the types of programs that the Engineering Detention Services have.
I think that he accepted them on their merit, not as second class.
He never did give me the feeling that we were second class to anybody, or to anybody else.
He always was fair.
He was very easy to talk to.
Who else?
Well, of course, Mr. Benson, I'm taking him from the top down now.
Mr. Benson and I had such a long-term relationship with each other.
We had it from about 55 to 54, whenever he became, until he got totally retired.
We had a good relationship after he retired.
Fred was always to the point, which I like.
Fred had a lot of character, you know.
He always...
I think Fred was a very smart individual.
He certainly commanded the
the attention of a lot of people.
When he spoke, a lot of people listened.
And I admired that in him.
So I'd have to put him on the top, and then of course the next man was Calhoun.
So I went out and talked to Calhoun.
We had a lot of working relationships together.
But in my opinion, I'm not saying one was better than the other, but in my opinion, we had completely different types of leadership.
After the middle 80s, it was completely different.
Did it become more bureaucratic?
Yes, it was strictly bureaucratic.
You didn't feel at ease picking up the phone and calling.
I never did it in the first place, but I always knew that I could if I wanted to talk to Dr. Williams or Calhoun.
I didn't have to worry about Dr. Williams or Calhoun chewing me out for calling Dr. Williams or vice versa.
Mr. Benson, I didn't ever do it.
to my knowledge, but I always felt comfortable in doing such a thing like that.
We were more, in my opinion, we were more professional.
We respected each other more.
We had a great deal of respect for each other.
And I think that was probably the one ingredient that made those change.
And I think before the time I retired in 92,
We had a closeness.
I felt to him as my friend, and not only as my boss, but my friend.
Other than your senior partners, whom did you turn to for advice and counsel and input most often?
To my committees.
I had advisory committees in every sector of my Engineering Detention Service program, made up of the leaders in their field.
Like a telephone association, I'd have top telephone members.
Power company, I'd have somebody from the power company.
And we had advisory committees.
We had one whole law advisory committee for the engineering attention.
It had one meeting a year.
And I'd call it in various parts of the state.
Other committee members would just pick up the phone and ask.
And I kept them informed.
If it was on my telephone committee, you got it.
And I didn't delude them with everything, but the things they ought to see, I sent it to them.
That's who I got help from, my users.
As you look back, can you think of any decisions you wish that Texas A&M had made that it didn't make?
Well, I think they should have gone forward and carried the intent of 15 years before we did.
I can't say that because I don't have the background.
All right.
Let's talk about that a minute.
Coeducation.
higher admission requirements, racial integration, broadening the curriculum, non-compulsory core, all those came in the 60s.
Did those affect your effort?
No.
No, they helped my effort.
You'd be surprised as to how many people, you know, I always traveled with an internship card.
That was my Roman billboard.
And you'd be surprised at the number of people that stopped me and asked me questions or to give them information.
I never took a trip that I didn't come back to and I didn't have four or five requests for information.
And, uh, questions just like you had, you know.
This girl was effective, you know.
And I'm not the one that's been effective.
Everybody helps.
The only one that's hurting it is people who don't want to join the program.
Now, you rode to Austin for a number of years to reserve meetings with Earl Rudder.
With Earl, I only went over there about six months with him because I'd always assigned a driver out of my unit to drive for him.
And when I quit that, it's because the last three that I assigned as a driver, they got them in Westport.
Oh, I see.
I see.
But I only filled in there for a period of about six months, I guess.
So, all right, during those years that you and Mr.
Rudder were going to the same meeting then in Austin, describe your relationship with him.

in reserve well of course mr rudder was a major general and i was a colonel and so rank-wise we was miles apart and i respected that i always addressed john rudder i never one time let myself down around children i always was reasonably formal we never did
What he did was, he was going to his meeting on Monday night, and you know, he'd have to be back.
He'd be back by 11.30, 12 o'clock.
Mr. Rutter, Mr. Rutter, nominally on the way back, slept.
And he had the ability to go to sleep.
He said, well, what did y'all discuss?
Well, we discussed the military quarter.
Discussed my unit.
I had a battle group.
We discussed military personnel quite a bit.

The university, the only thing that would come up about the university, you know, he'd ask you some questions that you really had no answer, and you'd say, well, let's just say I don't think he ever asked this question.
You're just thinking these are the type of questions he'd ask.
Well, has making the Corps adoptive of the persons coming to the university, that had any effect on you?
You know, I'd say, me, Perkins?
He'd say, well, Perkins and I do well.
I'd say, no, we're living in a different world.
And, you know, I said, I wouldn't take all the money in the world for my years I spent in the Corps for this.
I said, but, I said, that was in 1940.
And I said, I've got two sons.
And I said, they're both in the Corps, but I guarantee you I didn't push them in the Corps.
They went there on their own.
But we never did get into personalities.
We never did with me because, as I say, I was two ranks below him.
I didn't have any relationship with him as him being my boss other than in the military.
Can you share any anecdotes or amusing or interesting things that happened going to or from that involved Mr. Rutter?
No, but did anything ever go wrong?
Did you all ever have a flat or get there late or anything like that?
Well, I got stopped several times for speeding.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
And what would the highway patrol say?
Oh, he gave you, it didn't matter whose car that was?
We were driving a military vehicle.
Mr. Runner liked to get where he was going fast.
I don't know if anybody's ever told you that before.
No, I didn't know that.
He wasn't allergic to pushing the metal to the pedal.
I don't know how many tickets he got, but with me, I got one.
All right, who paid the tickets?
I gave it to him.
Okay, so you don't know.
You don't know, OK.
I never did ask him.
He always would take the ticket from me.
He took the one ticket from me.
All right, when the highway patrol would stop, did it impress the highway patrol that here was a major general?
Well, that only happened one time with me.
And I doubt if that highway patrol knew a major general.
All right, so he didn't even talk to the person in the back seat.
OK. No, I'm just talking about one time.
It was late at night.
Mr.
Rudder, have a sense of humor?
Very good sense of humor.

uh give me any can you give me an example of his i told you i had an infantry battle group and we always had the army commander come down when we go to camp so mr rudder always used my battle group as one to demonstrate him put on there today so one day we had this general come down fourth army commander you know i said to him i want to do this we'll be out of here training at 11 o'clock give me a map to tell me specifically where you're going to be all of these
So I said, fine, I've done this a dozen times.
So we decided to have an interview in a tank.
And I picked out a beautiful valley, and I had a nice row of trees.
And we come right, so I said, OK, we're going to come right down and do our tanks.
And so Bowman, Mr. Runner, and the other general go up.
I went up and reported to him.
Oh, he said, oh.
And I said to this gentleman, I said, now there's a lot of wood rattlers here up that wall.
And I said, in fact, I said, there's one right by your foot.
Oh, he's a little bit shorter than me.
And I said, put your boots on.
They won't bother you.
But anyway, we went up to this thing.
By that time, boy, everything was going to be different.
I mean, I had the idea.
I've always had the time right there.
They'd have a little awful time for attacking you.
So Mr. .
But anyway, I told this gentleman, I said, sir, I said, there's another rattlesnake that crashed by your foot, and I just put my foot back out and stopped it.
He said, get it back.
I said, no, sir, get it back.
So I got into his car.
He said, now, are you sure that rattlesnake didn't crash?
I said, I'll show you.
He said, I'd like to see you at 1 o'clock today, Carl.
And I thought he was going to get me for telling him about the damn rattlesnake.
He said, goddammit, Carl.
He said, when I said, make it realistic, he said, I didn't want you to run over us.
I said, well, I said, at that slope, I said, you know, I said, to make it realistic, we had to come take part in that slope.
He said, I didn't want it that damn close.
As far as you know, when Earl Rudder was president of A&M, to whom did he turn for advice most often?
Whose advice did he listen to most carefully?
Well, do you mean from in-house?
Mm-hmm.
I don't know.
All right, then you.
It might surprise you, though, if you didn't know.
There might be some instructor down there or something.
You said in-house.
All right, let's go out of the house.
Away from the campus, whose advice did he hear?
Well, he had here to the board's advice.
He had a lot of respect for the board.
Which, who were the key board members during his day?
Well, let's see.
He got out, when did he die, in 59?
Oh, in 70.
In 69?
Okay.
He died in March of 77.
Sterling Evans, Zachary, Clyde Wells.
Clyde Wells was on it, and Mrs. Wilson from Lubbock was on it.
And I don't know whether Norman Mosier was on it at that time.
I don't either.
And I don't know whether Mr.
